# {{WORKER_DISPLAY_NAME}} — authoring notes (OS-agnostic)

This is the rationale layer for the worker. It exists so a future reforge can pick up enough context to make a confident change without re-interviewing the user. Keep it strictly to answers that hold *regardless of OS* — the answers tied to one specific OS live in `<os>/<os>-specific.md`. It's allowed to read like notes — `WORKER.md` is the clean version.

## Original ask

What the user said in their own words. Paste it verbatim.

## Restatement

The one-paragraph spec you read back to the user and they confirmed.

## CODE-first alternatives considered

Cases where the task seemed to need a LOCAL or HOSTED unit and you proposed a CODE shape instead. For each: what you proposed, what the user said, why you accepted or rejected the CODE shape. (If every unit was obvious, this section is short — say so.)

## Interview answers (common to every OS)

- **Worker name (slug):** the kebab-case identifier used for the workspace folder and the `name:` field in `WORKER.md`.
- **Display name:** the human-readable name used in window titles, the about box, `WORKER.md`'s `# Heading`, and the artifact filename in `<os>/dist/` (e.g. `Manga Katana Watcher.exe`, not `manga-katana-watcher.exe`).
- **Trigger style:** double-click / CLI / GUI (mutually exclusive: double-click vs. GUI).
- **Icon:** default / user-provided (path to the file the user supplied, dropped into `<os>/resources/`).
- **Scheduling intent:** none / loop while running / start on boot / external scheduler (what the user *wants*; the per-OS glue lives in `<os>-specific.md`).
- **Color theme:** dark / light / user-provided (palette) / N/A if no GUI.
- **Data storage format:** sqlite / json / text / user-provided. (The *location* on disk is per-OS — record that in `<os>-specific.md`.)
- **UI description:** what windows/screens exist, what controls each one has, what the worker does on each interaction. Framework-agnostic.
- **Hosted providers used:** list each HOSTED unit and the provider/model picked.
- **Hosted-model auth strategy:** OS keyring / env var / config file. (The keyring backend differs per OS — that goes in `<os>-specific.md`.)

## Decisions and the reasoning

For each non-obvious choice, write a sentence or two on what you picked and why. Keep this OS-agnostic. Examples that future-you will want to see:

- "Picked JSON over SQLite for storage because the worker only writes a single timestamp per run; SQLite would be overkill."
- "Picked HOSTED Anthropic Claude for the summary unit because the input runs to ~30 pages and local models lose the thread."
- "Picked the single-binary distribution shape because the user wants to be able to email this to her assistant."

## Alternatives considered and rejected

Things you thought about and chose not to do. The discipline is to write these down even when the rejected option is dumb — future-you may be considering exactly that dumb option and the note saves the re-derivation.

## Edge cases the user signed off on

What the worker does when:

- The input is empty.
- Output already exists (overwrite / append / suffix / fail).
- Partial failure (one of N sources is down).
- It's the first run (initialization, baseline fetch).
- It's run twice in a row (idempotent or not).

## Reforge log

A timestamped append-only list of changes after the initial forge. Per-OS-only changes are fine to log here too, with the OS noted — gives a single chronological view of what's happened to the worker.

